<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910405-0048</DOCNO><DOCID>910405-0048.</DOCID><HL>   Waste Management's Chief   Got Big Pay Raise in 1990</HL><DATE>04/05/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8</SO><CO>   WMX</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>POLLUTION CONTROL, WASTE MANAGEMENT SERVICES (POL)INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL SERVICES (SVC)</IN><RE>ILLINOIS (IL)MIDDLE EAST (ML)</RE><LP>   OAK BROOK, Ill. -- It was a good year for garbage in 1990,as Waste Management Inc.'s chairman and chief executiveofficer, Dean L. Buntrock, was paid about $12.3 million insalary, bonuses and gains on stock options.   That was up sharply from 1989, when Mr. Buntrock's overallpay was about $1.35 million. The big increase came mostlyfrom exercising stock options, which added about $8 millionto his compensation in 1990, and from a three-year bonus planthat paid him $2.6 million last year, compared with nothingthe year before.</LP><TEXT>   As a group, the big trash hauler's four highest-paidexecutives' combined compensation was about $26.9 millionlast year: in addition to Mr. Buntrock, Philip B. Rooney,president, was paid $3.1 million in salary and bonus; JerryE. Dempsey, a senior vice president, was paid $7.7 million insalary, bonus and gains on stock options, and Donald F.Flynn, a senior vice president who retired Jan. 1, was paid$3.7 million in salary, bonus and gains on stock options.   Waste Management had a good year, too, with net income of$684.8 million, or $1.44 a share, on revenue of $6.03billion.   Separately, Waste Management said it received amonth-to-month contract, valued at $12 million annually, tobegin cleaning up the debris in Kuwait and to get regulargarbage collection there going again. The contract doesn'textend to some huge waste problems the nation is facing,including work on oil fields and hazardous wastes, or thehandling of construction debris from the eventual rebuildingin Kuwait.</TEXT></DOC>